The donation aims at stopping the entry of terrorists through those two provinces. The two provinces with records of terrorist attacks and where it has become imperative a greater control of borders, after it was found that it is through them that terrorists arrive in the country. The equipment includes radios, x-ray baggage inspection instruments, body scanners and patrol vehicles. The equipment resulted from an agreement on exchange of notes between the two governments and is valued at over $4 million. The relevance of the topic is that the donation is a reinforcement that will help to have greater and better control over the borders. This is not the first help from Japan in the efforts against armed violence in the north of the country. The equipment, valued at around $4 million, will strengthen border security in Cabo Delgado and Niassa provinces in northern Mozambique, Kimura Hajime told the media moments after signing the agreement providing support in Maputo. "The aim is to combat terrorism in Cabo Delgado because for us world peace is fundamental," Kimura Hajime stressed. The equipment is made up of scanning machines, radios and patrol vehicles, a donation that the Japanese government hopes will "strengthen Mozambique's capacity for border control and contribute to the country's socio-economic development. --ChannelAfrica--